Reference code/provenance for the `pda_ppi` benchmark.

  Fun/L2relax.R   The authors' L2-relaxation function, vendored verbatim from
                  github.com/ishwang1/L2relax-PDA (folder Fun/). Included for
                  provenance only -- a single function so a reader can see the
                  exact program the Python reference reproduces.
  reference.py    A faithful port of Fun/L2relax.R's convex program, solved with
                  cvxpy. It standardises the treated/donor pre-period series
                  exactly as the R function (intercept=TRUE, standardize=TRUE),
                  forms Sigma = X'X/T1 and eta = X'y/T1, minimises ||beta||^2
                  subject to |eta - Sigma beta| <= tau elementwise, then
                  de-standardises beta and the intercept. It reads the same
                  basedata/china_ppi_long.csv that mlsynth fits.

License / redistribution
  The L2relax-PDA repository ships NO explicit license file (checked: no
  LICENSE/COPYING and no SPDX header). We therefore do not redistribute the
  repository; we vendor only the single Fun/L2relax.R function for provenance
  (to document precisely which program the cvxpy port reproduces) and reproduce
  the *method* independently in reference.py. All credit for the method and the
  R implementation belongs to the authors (Shi & Wang).

Solver note
  The authors' default solver is CVXR (MOSEK in their notebooks; ECOS_BB in the
  L2relax.R signature). CVXR is NOT installable in this environment's R (no
  binary/source build of CVXR for R 4.3.3, and no MOSEK licence), so the
  identical convex program is run via cvxpy with the authors' default open
  solver family, ECOS. The L2-relaxation primal is strictly convex, so at a
  fixed tau the optimum is unique and solver-invariant; reference.py checks
  ECOS, OSQP, SCS and CLARABEL attain the same objective (solver_obj_spread).

These files produce the captured reference bundle only and are not part of the
mlsynth library.
